<section id="what-is-ro-crate" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="what-is-ro-crate">What Is RO-Crate?</h2>
<p><strong>RO-Crate</strong> (Research Object Crate) is a community standard for packaging research outputs — workflows, data, code, results — together with structured metadata that makes them self-describing.</p>
<p>The idea is simple: a folder of pipeline outputs means nothing to anyone except the person who ran it. An RO-Crate is that same folder with a <code>ro-crate-metadata.json</code> at the root that answers the questions any reader would ask:</p>
<ul>
<li>What is this?</li>
<li>Who created it?</li>
<li>What inputs were used?</li>
<li>What tools ran, at what versions?</li>
<li>What outputs were produced?</li>
<li>When did it run?</li>
</ul>
<p>The metadata uses <a href="https://schema.org">schema.org</a> vocabulary — the same structured data standard that underpins Google’s knowledge graph — which means it is both human-readable and machine-parseable by any system that understands the spec.</p>
<p>RO-Crate is not a new file format. It is a convention: any directory with a <code>ro-crate-metadata.json</code> that conforms to the <a href="https://www.researchobject.org/ro-crate/">RO-Crate specification</a> is a valid RO-Crate.</p>
<hr>
</section>
<section id="two-levels-of-ro-crate-in-a-nextflow-pipeline" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="two-levels-of-ro-crate-in-a-nextflow-pipeline">Two Levels of RO-Crate in a Nextflow Pipeline</h2>
<p>Before going further, it helps to understand that RO-Crate applies at two distinct levels in a Nextflow context:</p>
<table class="caption-top table">
<colgroup>
<col style="width: 16%">
<col style="width: 45%">
<col style="width: 38%">
</colgroup>
<thead>
<tr class="header">
<th>Level</th>
<th>What it describes</th>
<th>When it exists</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td><strong>Pipeline-level</strong></td>
<td>The workflow itself — purpose, authors, license, inputs, outputs</td>
<td>Once per pipeline, committed to the repo</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td><strong>Run-level</strong></td>
<td>A specific execution — input files, output files, parameters, container versions, timestamps</td>
<td>Generated fresh per pipeline run</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Both are valid RO-Crates. They serve different purposes. The pipeline-level one makes your workflow a citable, discoverable artifact. The run-level one is your audit trail and reproducibility record.</p>
<hr>
</section>
<section id="pipeline-level-ro-crate-describing-your-workflow" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="pipeline-level-ro-crate-describing-your-workflow">Pipeline-Level RO-Crate: Describing Your Workflow</h2>
<p>A pipeline-level <code>ro-crate-metadata.json</code> lives in the root of your pipeline repository. It describes your workflow as a <code>ComputationalWorkflow</code> — a scientific artifact with a name, authors, license, and formal descriptions of its inputs and outputs.</p>
