<section id="publishing-to-workflowhub" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="publishing-to-workflowhub">Publishing to WorkflowHub</h2>
<p><a href="https://workflowhub.eu/">WorkflowHub</a> is the community registry for FAIR scientific workflows. It reads your pipeline-level <code>ro-crate-metadata.json</code> directly to:</p>
<ul>
<li>Display pipeline metadata, authors, description, and inputs/outputs</li>
<li>Assign a <strong>DOI</strong> to your pipeline version, making it citable in publications</li>
<li>Link to bio.tools and Bioschemas entries for referenced software</li>
<li>Index your pipeline for discoverability across the research community</li>
</ul>
<p>Registering is straightforward: you provide a link to your repository or upload a zip, and WorkflowHub validates your RO-Crate and creates a landing page.</p>
<!--
  Add your nf-core template example here:
  Show the ro-crate-metadata.json that ships with the nf-core template
  and how WorkflowHub reads it for registered nf-core pipelines.
-->
<p>A DOI-backed WorkflowHub entry is also a portfolio item — a versioned, citable artifact with your name on it that you can link from your CV or LinkedIn.</p>
<hr>
</section>
<section id="why-this-matters-beyond-good-practice" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="why-this-matters-beyond-good-practice">Why This Matters Beyond Good Practice</h2>
<p>Three concrete reasons to invest time in RO-Crate now:</p>
<p><strong>Reproducibility is becoming a requirement.</strong> Journals, funders, and institutions increasingly require that computational analyses be reproducible. An <code>nf-prov</code> generated RO-Crate is concrete evidence — not just “here’s the code,” but “here’s the exact execution with checksums.”</p>
<p><strong>Client and audit requirements.</strong> Delivering pipeline outputs to external clients — pharma companies, hospitals, research institutes — often comes with a question: <em>can you prove what ran?</em> An RO-Crate run record is a ready-made answer.</p>
<p><strong>The bridge to regulated environments.</strong> Trusted Research Environments (TREs) — secure compute environments for sensitive clinical data used in NHS, UK Biobank, and EU health data spaces — require data provenance and audit trails by design. RO-Crate is one of the standards being evaluated and adopted to satisfy those requirements.</p>
<p>That last point is where this gets interesting, and where Part 2 of this series picks up.</p>
<hr>
</section>
